<p>More on the distinction between personal projects, personal chores, and other activities below.</p>

<p>"Personal projects" are generally tied to immediate or expected eventual output intended for public consumption, usually with some sort of "make the world better" goal. The key is that it should be "intended for public consumption" rather than "incidentally made public, but mainly for my own records." This could also include infrastructure work (e.g., work on server maintenance) that primarily supports such output.</p>

<p>"Personal chores" are chores I do for my own health and sustenance (excluding financial activities, that go under personal finances, income and taxes), including buying groceries, cooking, shopping, etc. It excludes regular daily activities (such as food and exercise) and also excludes very discretionary activities like eating out. Some high-level details of personal chores may be public but it is still not primarily intended for others' consumption. NOTE: Bank trips to withdraw cash are included in "personal chores" rather than personal finances.</p>

<p>"Other activities" is a broad umbrella term that covers a range of activities including chatting with friends and acquaintances on any topics where the goal is not to produce public output. Some time in other activities that is multiplexed with eating will not be included; time for picking up food from restaurants is also not included. It may also include time spent watching videos on YouTube or MasterClass that are not immediately tied to any public output I plan to produce. The same topic can shift from "other activities" to "personal projects" if I decide to produce public output related to it. For instance, if I watch or read something, it may initially go in "other activities" (and may not even be time-tracked) but if I later rewatch it with the goal of writing a public review, that rewatch time will go under personal projects.</p>

